Data analysis

Table

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.68) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.15. The model’s intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.46 (S.E. = 2.42, p < .001, 95% CI [8.71, 18.21]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically significant and positive (beta = 0.08, S.E. = 0.04, p = 0.044, 95% CI [2.28e-03, 0.17]; Std. beta = 0.31, 95% CI [8.40e-03, 0.61])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -1.00, S.E. = 1.20, p = 0.404, 95% CI [-3.34, 1.34]; Std. beta = -0.26, 95% CI [-0.86, 0.35])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.73, S.E. = 0.85, p = 0.390, 95% CI [-2.39, 0.93]; Std. beta = -0.19, 95% CI [-0.61, 0.24])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 3.84, S.E. = 1.25, p = 0.002, 95% CI [1.40, 6.28]; Std. beta = 0.99, 95% CI [0.36, 1.61])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
